# JLPT pattern research (public sources, no copying)

When generating JLPT-style questions, improve realism by researching **publicly available** information about JLPT structure and common patterns (by level N5–N1), then synthesize those patterns into **original** questions.

## Required behavior

- Prefer official or reputable public sources (JLPT format guides, skill breakdowns, published sample items, reputable prep publishers/blog analyses).
- Use research to extract **high-level patterns**, such as:
  - question types, section structure, timing/length expectations
  - grammar/vocabulary/kanji coverage tendencies by level
  - common distractor styles and difficulty ramps
- Produce **new, original** items that follow the patterns rather than reproducing existing questions.

## Avoid

- Copying or closely paraphrasing copyrighted test questions or answer explanations from past/archived tests.
- Including long excerpts from any source. Summarize patterns instead.
- Treating leaked/unauthorized “archives” as a data source.

